<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="295" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,152,827]" pageId="6" pageNumber="295">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,620,647]" pageId="6" pageNumber="295">Discussion.</emphasis>
The new species slightly resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Gorochov, 2008" authorityName="Gorochov" authorityYear="2008" box="[737,1321,621,647]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Alloteratura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="295" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curta" subGenus="Meconemopsis">
<emphasis box="[737,875,621,647]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="295">Alloteratura</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[891,1057,622,647]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="295">Meconemopsis</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1073,1132,622,647]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="295">curta</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Gorochov, A. V." box="[1139,1321,621,647]" pageId="6" pageNumber="295" pagination="26 - 42" refId="ref3324" refString="Gorochov, A. V. (2008) New and little known katydids of the tribe Meconematini (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae: Meconematinae) from south-east Asia. Proceedings of the Zoological Institute of the Russian Academy of Sciences, 312 (1 - 2), 26 - 42." type="journal article" year="2008">Gorochov, 2008</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but it differs from the latter in: male cercus stout, the middle area curved dorsally, inner margin concave, apical area slender, apex obtusely rounded. Epiphallus posterior margin with rectangular a notch in the middle, lateral margins each with 5 sclerotized spines directing dorsally (
<figureCitation box="[646,724,729,755]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1756,1781]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,489,1737]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,489,1737]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Alloteratura (Meconemopsis) pentadactyla sp. nov., male: A, D. pronotum: A. dorsal view; D. lateral view; B. maxillary palpus in lateral view; C. apex of genicular lobe of postfemur; F. subgenital plate in ventral view; E, G–H. apex of abdomen: E. lateral view; G dorsal view; H. ventral view; I. epiphallus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3363241/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="295">
Fig. 
<date box="[699,724,729,755]" pageId="6" pageNumber="295">3I</date>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="295" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,152,827]" pageId="6" pageNumber="295">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,765,791]" pageId="6" pageNumber="295">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name of new species is derived from inner margins of epiphallus with five sclerotized spines directing dorsally. Greek 
<emphasis box="[437,568,801,827]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="295">pentadactyl</emphasis>
- means five finger-shaped processes.
</paragraph>
